# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cockroachdb
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cockroachdb/blob-readme-md] CockroachDB is a cloud-native distributed SQL database designed to build, scale, and manage modern, data-intensive applications.
[src:cockroachdb/blob-readme-md] CockroachDB is a distributed SQL database built on a transactional and strongly-consistent key-value store.
[src:cockroachdb/blob-readme-md] It **scales** horizontally; **survives** disk, machine, rack, and even datacenter failures with minimal latency disruption and no manual intervention; supports **strongly-consistent** ACID transactions; and provides a familiar **SQL** API for structuring, manipulating, and querying data.
[src:cockroachdb/blob-readme-md] For more details, see our product overview, FAQ or architecture document.
[src:cockroachdb/blob-readme-md] For guidance on installation, development, deployment, and administration, see our User Documentation.
[src:cockroachdb/blob-readme-md] We can run CockroachDB for you, so you don't have to run your own cluster.
[src:cockroachdb/blob-readme-md] Start a local cluster and connect to it via the built-in SQL client.
[src:cockroachdb/blob-readme-md] Use a PostgreSQL-compatible driver or ORM to build an app with CockroachDB.
[src:cockroachdb/blob-readme-md] Explore core features, such as data replication, automatic rebalancing, and fault tolerance and recovery.
[src:cockroachdb/blob-readme-md] CockroachDB supports the PostgreSQL wire protocol, so you can use any available PostgreSQL client drivers to connect from various languages.
[src:cockroachdb/blob-readme-md] If you're looking for issues to work on, try looking at the good first issue list.
[src:cockroachdb/blob-readme-md] We do our best to tag issues suitable for new external contributors with that label, so it's a great way to find something you can help with!
[src:cockroachdb/blob-readme-md] Engineering discussions take place on our public mailing list, cockroach-db@googlegroups.com.
[src:cockroachdb/blob-readme-md] Also please join our Community Slack (there's a dedicated #contributors channel!) to ask questions, discuss your ideas, and connect with other contributors.
[src:cockroachdb/blob-readme-md] For an in-depth discussion of the CockroachDB architecture, see our Architecture Guide.
[src:cockroachdb/blob-readme-md] For the original design motivation, see our design doc.
[src:cockroachdb/blob-readme-md] All versions released on or after November 18, 2024 (specifically, major version series v24.3 and later, and patch fixes for v23.1.29+, v23.2.16+, v24.1.7+, and v24.2.5+) are published under the CockroachDB Software License (CSL).
[src:cockroachdb/blob-readme-md] Source code in a given file is licensed under the CSL and the copyright belongs to The Cockroach Authors unless otherwise noted in the file or in a LICENSE or README file located in the same or a parent directory of the file.
[src:cockroachdb/blob-readme-md] To see how key features of CockroachDB stack up against other databases, check out CockroachDB in Comparison.
[src:cockroachdb/cockroachdb] A CockroachDB cluster consists of a number of nodes that can be spread across failure domains such as data centres or public cloud regions.
[src:cockroachdb/cockroachdb] A cluster can be scaled both horizontally (by adding nodes) and vertically (by increasing the resources allocated to the existing nodes).
[src:cockroachdb/cockroachdb] It can provide high levels of resilience and availability and can be run in a variety of environments such as bare metal, VMs, containers and Kubernetes, both in private data centers and in the cloud.
[src:cockroachdb/cockroachdb] CockroachDB gets its name from cockroaches, as they are known for being disaster-resistant.
[src:cockroachdb/cockroachdb] Cockroach Labs was founded in 2015 by ex-Google employees Spencer Kimball, Peter Mattis, and Ben Darnell.
[src:cockroachdb/cockroachdb] Kimball and Mattis had been key members of the Google File System team, while Darnell was a key member of the Google Reader team.
[src:cockroachdb/cockroachdb] While at Google, all three had used Google-owned DBMS's Bigtable and its successor, Spanner.
[src:cockroachdb/cockroachdb] After leaving Google, they wanted to design and build something similar.
[src:cockroachdb/cockroachdb] Spencer Kimball wrote the first iteration of the design in January 2014, and began the open-source project on GitHub in February 2014, allowing outside access and contributions.
[src:cockroachdb/cockroachdb] Development on GitHub attracted substantial contributions, which earned the project the *Open Source Rookie of the Year* award by Black Duck Software.
[src:cockroachdb/cockroachdb] The co-founders supported the project with conferences, networking, meet-ups, and fund-raising financial rounds.
[src:cockroachdb/cockroachdb] CockroachDB stores copies of data in multiple locations to deliver quick access.
[src:cockroachdb/cockroachdb] It is described as a scalable, consistently-replicated, transactional data store.
[src:cockroachdb/cockroachdb] A single instance can scale from a single laptop to thousands of servers.
[src:cockroachdb/cockroachdb] CockroachDB is designed to run in the cloud and has a high fault tolerance.
[src:cockroachdb/cockroachdb] According to popular news outlets, it is described as “almost impossible” to take down.
[src:cockroachdb/cockroachdb] CockroachDB has a consistency model that is designed to match as closely as possible to the capabilities of Google Spanner, but without a dependence on specialized hardware for time synchronization.
[src:cockroachdb/cockroachdb] "No stale reads" is the simplest way to describe this consistency model which has deliberately made the trade-off of having non-linearizable transaction histories.
[src:cockroachdb/cockroachdb] Transactions containing overlapping keys are guaranteed to have external consistency.
[src:cockroachdb/distributed-database] A **distributed database** is a database in which data is stored across different physical locations.
[src:cockroachdb/distributed-database] It may be stored in multiple computers located in the same physical location (e.g. a data centre); or maybe dispersed over a network of interconnected computers.
[src:cockroachdb/distributed-database] Unlike parallel systems, in which the processors are tightly coupled and constitute a single database system, a distributed database system consists of loosely coupled sites that share no physical components.
[src:cockroachdb/distributed-database] System administrators can distribute collections of data (e.g. in a database) across multiple physical locations.
[src:cockroachdb/distributed-database] A distributed database can reside on organised network servers or decentralised independent computers on the Internet, on corporate intranets or extranets, or on other organisation networks.
[src:cockroachdb/distributed-database] Because distributed databases store data across multiple computers, distributed databases may improve performance at end-user worksites by allowing transactions to be processed on many machines, instead of being limited to one.
[src:cockroachdb/distributed-database] Two processes ensure that the distributed databases remain up-to-date and current: replication and duplication.
[src:cockroachdb/distributed-database] Duplication, on the other hand, has less complexity.
[src:cockroachdb/distributed-database] It identifies one database as a master and then duplicates that database.
[src:cockroachdb/distributed-database] The duplication process is normally done at a set time after hours.
[src:cockroachdb/distributed-database] This is to ensure that each distributed location has the same data.
[src:cockroachdb/distributed-database] In the duplication process, users may change only the master database.
[src:cockroachdb/distributed-database] This ensures that local data will not be overwritten.
[src:cockroachdb/distributed-database] Both replication and duplication can keep the data current in all distributive locations.
[src:cockroachdb/distributed-database] Besides distributed database replication and fragmentation, there are many other distributed database design technologies.
[src:cockroachdb/distributed-database] For example, local autonomy, synchronous, and asynchronous distributed database technologies.
[src:cockroachdb/distributed-database] The implementation of these technologies can and do depend on the needs of the business and the sensitivity/confidentiality of the data stored in the database and the price the business is willing to spend on ensuring data security, consistency and integrity.
[src:cockroachdb/distributed-database] In the shared-memory and shared-disk architectures, the data is not partitioned, but it has to be in a shared-nothing architecture.
[src:cockroachdb/distributed-database] Shared-disk architecture is more common for cloud databases than for on-premise.
[src:cockroachdb/distributed-database] Historically, shared-nothing was the first architecture to be implemented on the cloud, before the advent of shared cloud storage made shared-disk possible.
[src:cockroachdb/distributed-database] In practice, different layers of the database can have different architectures.
[src:cockroachdb/distributed-database] It is now common to have a compute layer with a shared nothing architecture, and a storage layer with a shared disk architecture.
[src:cockroachdb/distributed-database] This is for instance the case of Snowflake and AWS Aurora.
[src:cockroachdb/distributed-sql] A **distributed SQL** database is a single relational database which replicates data across multiple servers.
[src:cockroachdb/distributed-sql] Distributed SQL databases are strongly consistent and most support consistency across racks, data centers, and wide area networks including cloud availability zones and cloud geographic zones.
[src:cockroachdb/distributed-sql] Distributed SQL databases typically use the Paxos or Raft algorithms to achieve consensus across multiple nodes.
[src:cockroachdb/distributed-sql] Sometimes distributed SQL databases are referred to as NewSQL but NewSQL is a more inclusive term that includes databases that are not distributed databases.
[src:cockroachdb/distributed-sql] Google's Spanner popularized the modern distributed SQL database concept.
[src:cockroachdb/distributed-sql] Spanner uses atomic clocks with the Paxos algorithm to accomplish consensus with regards to state distributed between servers.
[src:cockroachdb/distributed-sql] In 2010, and earlier implementation, ClustrixDB (now MariaDB Xpand) moved from a hardware appliance to a Paxos-based software database and was later acquired by MariaDB and added to a SaaS cloud offering called SkySQL.
[src:cockroachdb/distributed-sql] In 2015, two Google engineers left the company to create Cockroach DB which achieves similar results using the Raft algorithm without atomic clocks or custom hardware.
[src:cockroachdb/distributed-sql] Spanner is primarily used for transactional and time-series use cases.
[src:cockroachdb/distributed-sql] However, Google furthered this research with a follow on paper about Google F1 which it describes as a Hybrid transactional/analytical processing database built on Spanner.
[src:cockroachdb/distributed-sql] Following the CAP Theorem, distributed SQL databases are "CP" or consistent and partition-tolerant.
[src:cockroachdb/distributed-sql] Algorithmically they sacrifice availability in that a failure of a primary node can make the database unavailable for writes.
[src:cockroachdb/distributed-sql] All distributed SQL implementations require some kind of temporal synchronization to guarantee consistency.
[src:cockroachdb/distributed-sql] With the exception of Spanner, most do not use custom hardware to provide atomic clocks.
[src:cockroachdb/distributed-sql] Spanner is able to synchronize writes with temporal guarantees.
[src:cockroachdb/distributed-sql] Implementations without custom hardware require servers to compare clock offsets and potentially retry reads.
[src:cockroachdb/distributed-sql] CockroachDB, YugabyteDB and others have at times referred to themselves as NewSQL databases.
[src:cockroachdb/distributed-sql] Some of the NewSQL databases have fundamentally different architectures, but were cited as examples of NewSQL by Matthew Aslett who coined the term.
[src:cockroachdb/distributed-sql] In essence, distributed SQL databases are built from the ground-up and NewSQL databases include replication and sharding technologies added to existing client-server relational databases like PostgreSQL.
[src:cockroachdb/distributed-sql] Some experts define DistributedSQL databases as a more specific subset of NewSQL databases.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] The distribution layer of CockroachDB's architecture provides a unified view of your cluster's data.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] If you haven't already, we recommend reading the Architecture Overview.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] To make all data in your cluster accessible from any node, CockroachDB stores data in a monolithic sorted map of key-value pairs.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] This key-space describes all of the data in your cluster, as well as its location, and is divided into what we call "ranges", contiguous chunks of the key-space, so that every key can always be found in a single range.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] The locations of all ranges in your cluster are stored in a two-level index at the beginning of your key-space, known as meta ranges, where the first level (`meta1`) addresses the second, and the second (`meta2`) addresses data in the cluster.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] This two-level index plus user data can be visualized as a tree, with the root at `meta1`, the second level at `meta2`, and the leaves of the tree made up of the ranges that hold user data.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] Importantly, every node has information on where to locate the `meta1` range (known as its range descriptor, detailed below), and the range is never split.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] This meta range structure lets us address up to 4EiB of user data by default: we can address 2^(18 + 18) = 2^36 ranges; each range addresses 2^26 B, and altogether we address 2^(36+26) B = 2^62 B = 4EiB.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] However, with larger range sizes, it's possible to expand this capacity even further.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] Meta ranges are treated mostly like normal ranges and are accessed and replicated just like other elements of your cluster's KV data.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] Each node caches values of the `meta2` range it has accessed before, which optimizes access of that data in the future.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] Whenever a node discovers that its `meta2` cache is invalid for a specific key, the cache is updated by performing a regular read on the `meta2` range.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] After the node's meta ranges is the KV data your cluster stores.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] Each table and its secondary indexes initially map to a single range, where each key-value pair in the range represents a single row in the table (also called the primary index because the table is sorted by the primary key) or a single row in a secondary index.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] As soon as a range reaches the default range size, it splits into two ranges.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] This process continues as a table and its indexes continue growing.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] Once a table is split across multiple ranges, it's likely that the table and secondary indexes will be stored in separate ranges.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] However, a range can still contain data for both the table and a secondary index.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] The default range size represents a sweet spot for us between a size that's small enough to move quickly between nodes, but large enough to store a meaningfully contiguous set of data whose keys are more likely to be accessed together.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] These ranges are then shuffled around your cluster to ensure survivability.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] These table ranges are replicated (in the aptly named replication layer), and have the addresses of each replica stored in the `meta2` range.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] This can also be visualized as a tree, with the root at `meta1`, the second level at `meta2`, and the leaves of the tree made up of the ranges that hold user data.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] When a node receives a request, it looks up the location of the range(s) that include the keys in the request in a bottom-up fashion, starting with the leaves of this tree.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] If the range's location is not found in the cache, the node looks up the location of the range where the actual value of `meta2` resides.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] This information is also cached; if the location of the `meta2` range is found in the cache, the node sends an RPC to the `meta2` range to get the location of the keys the request wants to operate on, and returns that information.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] Finally, if the location of the `meta2` range is not found in the cache, the node looks up the location of the range where the actual value of the first level of range metadata (`meta1`) resides.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] This lookup always succeeds because the location of `meta1` is distributed among all the nodes in the cluster using a gossip protocol.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] The node then uses the information from `meta1` to look up the location of `meta2`, and from `meta2` it looks up the locations of the ranges that include the keys in the request.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] Note that the process described above is recursive; every time a lookup is performed, it either (1) gets a location from the cache, or (2) performs another lookup on the value in the next level "up" in the tree.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] Because the range metadata is cached, a lookup can usually be performed without having to send an RPC to another node.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] Now that the node has the location of the range where the key from the request resides, it sends the KV operations from the request along to the range (using the `DistSender` machinery) in a `BatchRequest`.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] gRPC is the software nodes use to communicate with one another.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] Because the distribution layer is the first layer to communicate with other nodes, CockroachDB implements gRPC here.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] gRPC requires inputs and outputs to be formatted as protocol buffers (protobufs).
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] To leverage gRPC, CockroachDB implements a protocol-buffer-based API.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] By default, the network timeout for RPC connections between nodes is 2s, with a connection timeout of 4s, in order to reduce unavailability and tail latencies during infrastructure outages.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] This can be changed via the environment variable `COCKROACH_NETWORK_TIMEOUT`, which defaults to 2s.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] Note that the gRPC network timeouts described above are defined from the server's point of view, not the client's (the client is any other node that is trying to make an inbound connection).
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] From the client, we send an additional RPC ping every 1s to check that connections are alive.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] These pings have a fairly high timeout of 6s (a multiple of the value of `COCKROACH_NETWORK_TIMEOUT`) because they are subject to contention with other RPC traffic; e.g., during a large `IMPORT INTO` they can be delayed by several seconds.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] For more information about gRPC, see the official gRPC documentation.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] All KV operation requests are bundled into a protobuf, known as a `BatchRequest`.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] The destination of this batch is identified in the `BatchRequest` header, as well as a pointer to the request's transaction record.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] This `BatchRequest` is also what's used to send requests between nodes using gRPC, which accepts and sends protocol buffers.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] The gateway/coordinating node's `DistSender` receives `BatchRequest`s from its own `TxnCoordSender`.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] `DistSender` is then responsible for breaking up `BatchRequests` and routing a new set of `BatchRequests` to the nodes it identifies contain the data using the system meta ranges.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] For a description of the process by which this lookup from a key to the node holding the key's range is performed, see Using the monolithic sorted map.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] It sends the `BatchRequest`s to the replicas of a range, ordered in expectation of request latency.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] The leaseholder is tried first, if the request needs it.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] Requests received by a non-leaseholder may fail with an error pointing at the replica's last known leaseholder.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] These requests are retried transparently with the updated lease by the gateway node and never reach the client.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] As nodes begin replying to these commands, `DistSender` also aggregates the results in preparation for returning them to the client.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] Like all other data in your cluster, meta ranges are structured as KV pairs.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] In this case, the replica on `node1` is the leaseholder, and nodes 2 and 3 also contain replicas.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] Let's imagine we have an alphabetically sorted column, which we use for lookups.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] The table itself is stored with an `index_id` of 1 for its `PRIMARY KEY` columns, with the rest of the columns in the table considered as stored/covered columns.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] Each range in CockroachDB contains metadata, known as a range descriptor.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] Because range descriptors comprise the key-value data of the `meta2` range, each node's `meta2` cache also stores range descriptors.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] All of these updates to the range descriptor occur locally on the range, and then propagate to the `meta2` range.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] By default, CockroachDB attempts to keep ranges/replicas at the default range size.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] Once a range reaches that limit, we split it into two smaller ranges (composed of contiguous key spaces).
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] During this range split, the node creates a new Raft group containing all of the same members as the range that was split.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] The fact that there are now two ranges also means that there is a transaction that updates `meta2` with the new keyspace boundaries, as well as the addresses of the nodes using the range descriptor.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] By default, CockroachDB automatically merges small ranges of data together to form fewer, larger ranges (up to the default range size).
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] This can improve both query latency and cluster survivability.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] As described above, CockroachDB splits your cluster's data into many ranges.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] For example, your cluster might have a range for customers whose IDs are between `[1000, 2000)`.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] If that range grows beyond the default range size, the range is split into two smaller ranges.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] However, as you delete data from your cluster, a range might contain far less data than the default range size.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] Over the lifetime of a cluster, this could lead to a number of small ranges.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] To reduce the number of small ranges, your cluster can have any range below a certain size threshold try to merge with its "right-hand neighbor", i.e., the range that starts where the current range ends.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] Using our example above, this range's right-hand neighbor might be the range for customers whose IDs are between `[2000, 3000)`.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] If the combined size of the small range and its neighbor is less than the maximum range size, the ranges merge into a single range.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] In our example, this will create a new range of keys `[1000, 3000)`.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] When ranges merge, the left-hand-side (LHS) range consumes the right-hand-side (RHS) range.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] Queries in CockroachDB must contact a replica of each range involved in the query.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] By merging small ranges, CockroachDB can greatly reduce the number of ranges involved in queries, thus reducing query latency.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] CockroachDB automatically rebalances the distribution of ranges in your cluster whenever nodes come online or go offline.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] During rebalancing, it's better to replicate a few larger ranges across nodes than many smaller ranges.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] Replicating larger ranges requires less coordination and often completes more quickly.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] By merging smaller ranges together, your cluster needs to rebalance fewer total ranges.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] This ultimately improves your cluster's performance, especially in the face of availability events like node outages.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] The distribution layer's `DistSender` receives `BatchRequests` from its own node's `TxnCoordSender`, housed in the transaction layer.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] The distribution layer routes `BatchRequests` to nodes containing ranges of data, which is ultimately routed to the Raft group leader and leaseholder, which are handled in the replication layer.
[src:cockroachdb/distribution-layer] Learn how CockroachDB copies data and ensures consistency in the replication layer.
[src:cockroachdb/overview] CockroachDB was designed to create the source-available database we would want to use: one that is both scalable and consistent.
[src:cockroachdb/overview] Developers often have questions about how we've achieved this, and this guide sets out to detail the inner workings of the `cockroach` process as a means of explanation.
[src:cockroachdb/overview] However, you definitely do not need to understand the underlying architecture to use CockroachDB.
[src:cockroachdb/overview] These pages give serious users and database enthusiasts a high-level framework to explain what's happening under the hood.
[src:cockroachdb/overview] If these docs interest you, consider taking the free Intro to Distributed SQL course on Cockroach University.
[src:cockroachdb/overview] This guide is broken out into pages detailing each layer of CockroachDB.
[src:cockroachdb/overview] We recommended reading through the layers sequentially, starting with this overview and then proceeding to the SQL layer.
[src:cockroachdb/overview] If you're looking for a high-level understanding of CockroachDB, you can read the **Overview** section of each layer.
[src:cockroachdb/overview] For more technical detail — for example, if you're interested in contributing to the project — you should read the **Components** sections as well.
[src:cockroachdb/overview] This guide details how CockroachDB is built, but does not explain how to build an application using CockroachDB.
[src:cockroachdb/overview] For more information about how to develop applications that use CockroachDB, check out our Developer Guide.
[src:cockroachdb/overview] With the confluence of these features, we hope that CockroachDB helps you build global, scalable, resilient deployments and applications.
[src:cockroachdb/overview] Once the CockroachDB cluster is initialized, developers interact with CockroachDB through a PostgreSQL-compatible SQL API.
[src:cockroachdb/overview] Thanks to the symmetrical behavior of all nodes in a cluster, you can send SQL requests to any node; this makes CockroachDB easy to integrate with load balancers.
[src:cockroachdb/overview] After receiving SQL remote procedure calls (RPCs), nodes convert them into key-value (KV) operations that work with our distributed, transactional key-value store.
[src:cockroachdb/overview] As these RPCs start filling your cluster with data, CockroachDB starts algorithmically distributing your data among the nodes of the cluster, breaking the data up into chunks that we call ranges.
[src:cockroachdb/overview] Each range is replicated to at least 3 nodes by default to ensure survivability.
[src:cockroachdb/overview] If a node receives a read or write request it cannot directly serve, it finds the node that can handle the request, and communicates with that node.
[src:cockroachdb/overview] This means you do not need to know where in the cluster a specific portion of your data is stored; CockroachDB tracks it for you, and enables symmetric read/write behavior from each node.
[src:cockroachdb/overview] Any changes made to the data in a range rely on a consensus algorithm to ensure that the majority of the range's replicas agree to commit the change.
[src:cockroachdb/overview] This is how CockroachDB achieves the industry-leading isolation guarantees that allow it to provide your application with consistent reads and writes, regardless of which node you communicate with.
[src:cockroachdb/overview] Ultimately, data is written to and read from disk using an efficient storage engine, which is able to keep track of the data's timestamp.
[src:cockroachdb/overview] This has the benefit of letting us support the SQL standard `AS OF SYSTEM TIME` clause, letting you find historical data for a period of time.
[src:cockroachdb/overview] While the high-level overview above gives you a notion of what CockroachDB does, looking at how CockroachDB operates at each of these layers will give you much greater understanding of our architecture.
[src:cockroachdb/overview] At the highest level, CockroachDB converts clients' SQL statements into key-value (KV) data, which is distributed among nodes and written to disk.
[src:cockroachdb/overview] CockroachDB's architecture is manifested as a number of layers, each of which interacts with the layers directly above and below it as relatively opaque services.
[src:cockroachdb/overview] The following pages describe the function each layer performs, while mostly ignoring the details of other layers.
[src:cockroachdb/overview] This description is true to the experience of the layers themselves, which generally treat the other layers as black-box APIs.
[src:cockroachdb/overview] There are some interactions that occur between layers that require an understanding of each layer's function to understand the entire process.
[src:cockroachdb/overview] The requirement that a transaction must change affected data only in allowed ways.
[src:cockroachdb/overview] CockroachDB uses "consistency" in both the sense of ACID semantics and the CAP theorem, albeit less formally than either definition.
[src:cockroachdb/overview] The degree to which a transaction may be affected by other transactions running at the same time.
[src:cockroachdb/overview] CockroachDB provides the `SERIALIZABLE` and `READ COMMITTED` isolation levels.
[src:cockroachdb/overview] For more information, see Isolation levels.
[src:cockroachdb/overview] The process of reaching agreement on whether a transaction is committed or aborted.
[src:cockroachdb/overview] CockroachDB uses the Raft consensus protocol.
[src:cockroachdb/overview] In CockroachDB, when a range receives a write, a quorum of nodes containing replicas of the range acknowledge the write.
[src:cockroachdb/overview] This means your data is safely stored and a majority of nodes agree on the database's current state, even if some of the nodes are offline.
[src:cockroachdb/overview] When a write does not achieve consensus, forward progress halts to maintain consistency within the cluster.
[src:cockroachdb/overview] The process of creating and distributing copies of data, as well as ensuring that those copies remain consistent.
[src:cockroachdb/overview] CockroachDB requires all writes to propagate to a quorum of copies of the data before being considered committed.
[src:cockroachdb/overview] This ensures the consistency of your data.
[src:cockroachdb/overview] A set of operations performed on a database that satisfy the requirements of ACID semantics.
[src:cockroachdb/overview] This is a crucial feature for a consistent system to ensure developers can trust the data in their database.
[src:cockroachdb/overview] For more information about how transactions work in CockroachDB, see Transaction Layer.
[src:cockroachdb/overview] Steps should be taken to reduce transaction contention in the first place.
[src:cockroachdb/overview] A consensus-based notion of high availability that lets each node in the cluster handle reads and writes for a subset of the stored data (on a per-range basis).
[src:cockroachdb/overview] This is in contrast to *active-passive replication*, in which the active node receives 100% of request traffic, and *active-active* replication, in which all nodes accept requests but typically cannot guarantee that reads are both up-to-date and fast.
[src:cockroachdb/overview] A SQL user is an identity capable of executing SQL statements and performing other cluster actions against CockroachDB clusters.
[src:cockroachdb/overview] SQL users must authenticate with an option permitted on the cluster (username/password, single sign-on (SSO), or certificate).
[src:cockroachdb/overview] Note that a SQL/cluster user is distinct from a CockroachDB Cloud organization user.
[src:cockroachdb/overview] A group of interconnected CockroachDB nodes that function as a single distributed SQL database server.
[src:cockroachdb/overview] Nodes collaboratively organize transactions, and rebalance workload and data storage to optimize performance and fault-tolerance.
[src:cockroachdb/overview] Each cluster has its own authorization hierarchy, meaning that users and roles must be defined on that specific cluster.
[src:cockroachdb/overview] A CockroachDB cluster can be run in CockroachDB Cloud, within a customer Organization, or can be self-hosted.
[src:cockroachdb/overview] CockroachDB stores all user data (tables, indexes, etc.) and almost all system data in a sorted map of key-value pairs.
[src:cockroachdb/overview] This keyspace is divided into contiguous chunks called *ranges*, such that every key is found in one range.
[src:cockroachdb/overview] From a SQL perspective, a table and its secondary indexes initially map to a single range, where each key-value pair in the range represents a single row in the table (also called the *primary index* because the table is sorted by the primary key) or a single row in a secondary index.
[src:cockroachdb/overview] As soon as the size of a range reaches the default range size, it is split into two ranges.
[src:cockroachdb/overview] This process continues for these new ranges as the table and its indexes continue growing.
[src:cockroachdb/overview] By default, there are three replicas of each range on different nodes.
[src:cockroachdb/overview] The replica that holds the "range lease." This replica receives and coordinates all read and write requests for the range.
[src:cockroachdb/overview] For most types of tables and queries, the leaseholder is the only replica that can serve consistent reads (reads that return "the latest" data).
[src:cockroachdb/overview] The leaseholder is always the same replica as the Raft leader, except briefly during lease transfers.
[src:cockroachdb/overview] For more information, refer to Leader leases.
[src:cockroachdb/overview] The consensus protocol employed in CockroachDB that ensures that your data is safely stored on multiple nodes and that those nodes agree on the current state even if some of them are temporarily disconnected.
[src:cockroachdb/overview] For each range, the replica that is the "leader" for write requests.
[src:cockroachdb/overview] The leader uses the Raft protocol to ensure that a majority of replicas (the leader and enough followers) agree, based on their Raft logs, before committing the write.
[src:cockroachdb/overview] The Raft leader is always the same replica as the leaseholder.
[src:cockroachdb/overview] A time-ordered log of writes to a range that its replicas have agreed on.
[src:cockroachdb/overview] This log exists on-disk with each replica and is the range's source of truth for consistent replication.
[src:cockroachdb/overview] Start by learning about what CockroachDB does with your SQL statements at the SQL layer.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] The replication layer of CockroachDB's architecture copies data between nodes and ensures consistency between these copies by implementing our consensus algorithm.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] High availability requires that your database can tolerate nodes going offline without interrupting service to your application.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] This means replicating data between nodes to ensure the data remains accessible.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] Ensuring consistency with nodes offline, though, is a challenge many databases fail.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] To solve this problem, CockroachDB uses a consensus algorithm to require that a quorum of replicas agrees on any changes to a range before those changes are committed.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] Because 3 is the smallest number that can achieve quorum (i.e., 2 out of 3), CockroachDB's high availability (known as multi-active availability) requires 3 nodes.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] The number of failures that can be tolerated is equal to *(Replication factor - 1)/2*.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] For example, with 3x replication, one failure can be tolerated; with 5x replication, two failures, and so on.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] You can control the replication factor at the cluster, database, and table level using replication zones.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] When failures happen, though, CockroachDB automatically realizes nodes have stopped responding and works to redistribute your data to continue maximizing survivability.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] This process also works the other way around: when new nodes join your cluster, data automatically rebalances onto them, ensuring your load is evenly distributed.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] Raft is a consensus protocol––an algorithm which makes sure that your data is safely stored on multiple machines, and that those machines agree on the current state even if some of them are temporarily disconnected.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] Raft organizes all nodes that contain a replica of a range into a group--unsurprisingly called a Raft group.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] Each replica in a Raft group is either a "leader" or a "follower".
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] The leader, which is elected by Raft and long-lived, coordinates all writes to the Raft group.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] It heartbeats followers periodically and keeps their logs replicated.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] In the absence of heartbeats, followers become candidates after randomized election timeouts and proceed to hold new leader elections.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] A third replica type, the "non-voting" replica, does not participate in Raft elections, but is useful for unlocking use cases that require low-latency multi-region reads.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] For more information, see Non-voting replicas.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] For the current values of the Raft election timeout, the Raft proposal timeout, and other important intervals, see Important values and timeouts.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] Once a node receives a `BatchRequest` for a range it contains, it converts those KV operations into Raft commands.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] Those commands are proposed to the Raft group leader––which is also the leaseholder––and written to the Raft log.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] For a great overview of Raft, we recommend The Secret Lives of Data.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] When writes receive a quorum, and are committed by the Raft group leader, they're appended to the Raft log.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] This provides an ordered set of commands that the replicas agreed on and is essentially the source of truth for consistent replication.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] Because this log is treated as serializable, it can be replayed to bring a node from a past state to its current state.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] This log also lets nodes that temporarily went offline to be "caught up" to the current state without needing to receive a copy of the existing data in the form of a snapshot.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] In versions prior to v21.1, CockroachDB only supported *voting* replicas: that is, replicas that participate as voters in the Raft consensus protocol.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] However, the need for all replicas to participate in the consensus algorithm meant that increasing the replication factor came at a cost of increased write latency, since the additional replicas needed to participate in Raft quorum.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] In order to provide better support for multi-region clusters (including the features that make fast multi-region reads and surviving region failures possible), a new type of replica was introduced: the *non-voting* replica.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] Non-voting replicas follow the Raft log (and are thus able to serve follower reads), but do not participate in quorum.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] They have almost no impact on write latencies.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] They are also sometimes referred to as *read-only* replicas, since they only serve reads, but do not participate in quorum (and thus do not incur the associated latency costs).
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] Non-voting replicas can be configured via zone configurations through `num_voters` and `num_replicas`.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] When `num_voters` is configured to be less than `num_replicas`, the difference dictates the number of non-voting replicas.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] However, most users should control non-voting replica placement with the high-level multi-region SQL features instead.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] When individual ranges become temporarily unavailable, requests to those ranges are refused by a per-replica "circuit breaker" mechanism instead of hanging indefinitely.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] These (hopefully transient) errors are also signalled as events in the DB Console's Replication Dashboard and as "circuit breaker errors" in its **Problem Ranges** and **Range Status** pages.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] Meanwhile, CockroachDB continues asynchronously probing the range's availability.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] If the replica becomes available again, the breaker is reset so that it can go back to serving requests normally.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] This feature is designed to increase the availability of your CockroachDB clusters by making them more robust to transient errors.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] Per-replica circuit breakers are enabled by default.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] Most users will not have to configure anything to get the benefits of this feature.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] The circuit breaker timeout value is controlled by the `kv.replica_circuit_breaker.slow_replication_threshold` cluster setting, which defaults to an interval of `1m0s` (1 minute).
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] Each replica can be "snapshotted", which copies all of its data as of a specific timestamp (available because of MVCC).
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] This snapshot can be sent to other nodes during a rebalance event to expedite replication.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] After loading the snapshot, the node gets up to date by replaying all actions from the Raft group's log that have occurred since the snapshot was taken.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] CockroachDB clusters running v23.1 and later can send *delegated snapshots*.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] Delegated snapshots can be sent by a Raft follower on behalf of the leader of a range.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] Which follower is chosen depends on the locality of the follower being nearest the replica that is the final recipient of the snapshot.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] If the follower is not able to send the snapshot quickly, the attempt is cancelled and the Raft leader sends the snapshot instead.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] If the follower is not able to send a snapshot that will be valid for the recipient, the request is rerouted to the leader.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] Delegated snapshots are managed automatically by the cluster with no need for user involvement.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] To limit the impact of snapshot ingestion on a node with a provisioned rate configured for its store, CockroachDB can apply admission control to snapshot transfer based on disk bandwidth.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] This allows you to limit the disk impact on foreground workloads on the node.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] When `kvadmission.store.provisioned_bandwidth` is set to a non-zero value and disk-bandwidth admission control is enabled (via `admission.disk_bandwidth_tokens.elastic.enabled`), snapshot ingestion is subject to this control by default.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] To disable snapshot-ingest bandwidth control, set the cluster setting `kvadmission.store.snapshot_ingest_bandwidth_control.enabled` to `false`.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] The related cluster setting `kvadmission.store.snapshot_ingest_bandwidth_control.min_rate.enabled` keeps snapshot ingestion moving at a minimum rate so it is not starved by other elastic work and can continue to make progress.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] The metrics `admission.wait_durations.snapshot_ingest` and `admission.admitted_snapshot_bytes` let you observe snapshot-ingest wait time and admitted bytes.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] A single node in the Raft group acts as the leaseholder, which is the only node that can serve reads or propose writes to the Raft group leader (both actions are received as `BatchRequests` from `DistSender`).
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] CockroachDB ensures that the leaseholder is also the Raft group leader via the Leader leases mechanism.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] This optimizes the speed of writes, and makes the cluster more robust against network partitions and node liveness failures.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] When the leaseholder is sent a write request, a majority of the replica nodes must be able to communicate with each other to coordinate the write.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] This ensures that the most recent write is always available to subsequent reads.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] If there is no leaseholder, any node receiving a request will attempt to become the leaseholder for the range.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] To extend its leases, each node must also remain the Raft leader, as described in Leader leases.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] When a node disconnects, it stops updating its *store liveness*, causing the node to lose all of its leases.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] A table's meta and system ranges (detailed in Distribution Layer) are treated as normal key-value data, and therefore have leases just like table data.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] When serving strongly-consistent (aka "non-stale") reads, leaseholders bypass Raft; for the leaseholder's writes to have been committed in the first place, they must have already achieved consensus, so a second consensus on the same data is unnecessary.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] This has the benefit of not incurring latency from networking round trips required by Raft and greatly increases the speed of reads (without sacrificing consistency).
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] CockroachDB is considered a CAP-Consistent (CP) system under the CAP theorem.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] CockroachDB prioritizes data consistency, but also provides high-availability due to the coordination between leaseholders and replicas, minimizing the tradeoff between consistency and availability outlined by the CAP theorem.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] When you store data in CockroachDB, the data will be valid and anomaly-free, even in the event of a system error or power failure.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] The range lease is always colocated with Raft leadership via the Leader leases mechanism, except briefly during lease transfers.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] This reduces network round trips since the leaseholder receiving the requests can simply propose the Raft commands to itself, rather than communicating them to another node.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] It also increases robustness against network partitions and outages due to liveness failures.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] Epoch-based leases are disabled by default in favor of Leader leases.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] To manage leases for table data, CockroachDB implements a notion of "epochs," which are defined as the period between a node joining a cluster and a node disconnecting from a cluster.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] To extend its leases, each node must periodically update its liveness record, which is stored on a system range key.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] When a node disconnects, it stops updating the liveness record, and the epoch is considered changed.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] This causes the node to lose all of its leases a few seconds later when the liveness record expires.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] Because leases do not expire until a node disconnects from a cluster, leaseholders do not have to individually renew their own leases.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] Tying lease lifetimes to node liveness in this way lets us eliminate a substantial amount of traffic and Raft processing we would otherwise incur, while still tracking leases for every range.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] A table's meta and system ranges (detailed in the distribution layer) are treated as normal key-value data, and therefore have leases just like table data.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] Unlike table data, system ranges use expiration-based leases; expiration-based leases expire at a particular timestamp (typically after a few seconds).
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] However, as long as a node continues proposing Raft commands, it continues to extend the expiration of its leases.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] If it doesn't, the next node containing a replica of the range that tries to read from or write to the range will become the leaseholder.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] Expiration-based leases are also used temporarily during operations like lease transfers, until the new Raft leader can be fortified based on store liveness, as described in Leader leases.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] Epoch-based leases (unlike Leader leases) are vulnerable to *leader-leaseholder splits*.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] These can occur when a leaseholder's Raft log has fallen behind other replicas in its group and it cannot acquire Raft leadership.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] Coupled with a network partition, this split can cause permanent unavailability of the range if (1) the stale leaseholder continues heartbeating the liveness range to hold its lease but (2) cannot reach the leader to propose writes.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] Symptoms of leader-leaseholder splits include a stalled Raft log on the leaseholder and increased disk usage on follower replicas buffering pending Raft entries.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] CockroachDB offers an improved leasing system rebuilt atop a stronger form of Raft leadership that ensures that the Raft leader is always the range's leaseholder, except briefly during lease transfers.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] This type of lease is called a *Leader lease*, and supersedes the former system of having different epoch-based and expiration-based lease types, while combining the performance of the former with the resilience of the latter.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] Leader leases rely on a shared, store-wide failure detection mechanism for triggering new Raft elections.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] Stores participate in Raft leader elections by "fortifying" a candidate replica based on that replica's *store liveness*, as determined among a quorum of all the node's stores.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] A replica can **only** become the Raft leader if it is so fortified.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] After the fortified Raft leader is chosen, it is then also established as the leaseholder.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] Support for the lease is provided as long as the Raft leader's store liveness remains supported by a quorum of stores in the Raft group.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] This provides the fortified Raft leader with a guarantee that it will not lose leadership until **after** it has lost store liveness support.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] This guarantee enables a number of improvements to the performance and resiliency of CockroachDB's Raft implementation that were prevented by the need to handle cases where Raft leadership and range leases were not colocated.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] Importantly, since Leader leases rely on a quorum of stores in the Raft group, they remove the need for the single point of failure (SPOF) that was the node liveness range.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] As a result, Leader leases are not vulnerable to the scenario possible under the previous leasing regime (prior to CockroachDB v25.2) where a leaseholder was partitioned from its followers (including a follower that was the Raft leader) but still heartbeating the node liveness range.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] Before Leader leases, this scenario would result in an indefinite outage that lasted as long as the lease was held by the partitioned node.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] For the purposes of Raft replication and determining the leaseholder of a range, node health is no longer determined by heartbeating a single "liveness range"; instead it is determined using Leader leases.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] When a cluster needs to access a range on a leaseholder node that is dead, the lease must be transferred to a healthy node.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] Raft Leadership Election: A Raft election is initiated to establish a new leader for the range.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] This step is necessary because lease acquisition can only occur on the Raft leader.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] The election process includes a store liveness component to fortify the new leader, as described in Leader leases.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] Lease Acquisition: Once a new Raft leader is elected, the lease acquisition process can proceed.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] The entire process, from detecting the node failure to acquiring the lease on a new node, should complete within a few seconds.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] This process is lazily initiated and only occurs when a new request is made that requires access to the range associated with the lease on the dead node.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] Because CockroachDB serves reads from a range's leaseholder, it benefits your cluster's performance if the replica closest to the primary geographic source of traffic holds the lease.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] However, as traffic to your cluster shifts throughout the course of the day, you might want to dynamically shift which nodes hold leases.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] This feature is also called Follow-the-Workload in our documentation.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] If all the replicas are in the same locality, the decision is made entirely on the basis of the number of leases on each node that contains a replica, trying to achieve a roughly equitable distribution of leases across all of them.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] This means the distribution isn't perfectly equal; it intentionally tolerates small deviations between nodes to prevent thrashing (i.e., excessive adjustments trying to reach an equilibrium).
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] If replicas are in different localities, CockroachDB attempts to calculate which replica would make the best leaseholder, i.e., provide the lowest latency.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] To enable dynamic leaseholder rebalancing, a range's current leaseholder tracks how many requests it receives from each locality as an exponentially weighted moving average.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] This calculation results in the locality that has recently requested the range most often being assigned the greatest weight.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] If another locality then begins requesting the range very frequently, this calculation would shift to assign the second region the greatest weight.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] When checking for leaseholder rebalancing opportunities, the leaseholder correlates each requesting locality's weight (i.e., the proportion of recent requests) to the locality of each replica by checking how similar the localities are.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] The leaseholder then evaluates its own weight and latency versus the other replicas to determine an adjustment factor.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] The greater the disparity between weights and the larger the latency between localities, the more CockroachDB favors the node from the locality with the larger weight.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] When checking for leaseholder rebalancing opportunities, the current leaseholder evaluates each replica's rebalancing weight and adjustment factor for the localities with the greatest weights.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] If moving the leaseholder is both beneficial and viable, the current leaseholder will transfer the lease to the best replica.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] You can control leaseholder rebalancing through the `kv.allocator.load_based_lease_rebalancing.enabled` cluster setting.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] Note that depending on the needs of your deployment, you can exercise additional control over the location of leases and replicas by configuring replication zones.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] Whenever there are changes to a cluster's number of nodes, the members of Raft groups change and, to ensure optimal survivability and performance, replicas need to be rebalanced.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] What that looks like varies depending on whether the membership change is nodes being added or going offline.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] CockroachDB does not always try to match the replica counts across nodes after adding nodes, decommissioning and removing nodes, or when there is a node outage.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] The replica allocator can keep replica counts uneven when that placement is needed to preserve survivability across localities or to satisfy replica placement constraints.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] For example, if a node is the only one in its availability zone in a 2-2-1 deployment across 3 AZs, that node may need to hold a replica for every range to preserve locality diversity, thus holding more replicas than its peers.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] Rebalancing is achieved by using a snapshot of a replica from the leaseholder, and then sending the data to another node over gRPC.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] After the transfer has been completed, the node with the new replica joins that range's Raft group; it then detects that its latest timestamp is behind the most recent entries in the Raft log and it replays all of the actions in the Raft log on itself.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] The preceding load-based goals do not override replica placement constraints or survivability requirements, so replica counts can remain uneven when CockroachDB needs a specific placement to respect placement constraints or preserve locality diversity.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] Note that disk utilization per node is not one of the rebalancing criteria.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] For more information, see Disk utilization is different across nodes in the cluster.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] Load-based replica rebalancing operates in conjunction with load-based splitting of ranges.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] Depending on the needs of your deployment, you can exercise additional control over the locations of leases and replicas using multi-region SQL, or by configuring replication zones.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] The replication layer receives requests from its and other nodes' `DistSender`.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] If this node is the leaseholder for the range, it accepts the requests; if it isn't, it returns an error with a pointer to which node it believes *is* the leaseholder.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] These KV requests are then turned into Raft commands.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] The replication layer sends `BatchResponses` back to the distribution layer's `DistSender`.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] Committed Raft commands are written to the Raft log and ultimately stored on disk through the storage layer.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] The leaseholder serves reads from the storage layer.
[src:cockroachdb/replication-layer] Learn how CockroachDB reads and writes data from disk in the storage layer.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] The storage layer of CockroachDB's architecture reads and writes data to disk.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] Each CockroachDB node contains at least one `store`, specified when the node starts, which is where the `cockroach` process reads and writes its data on disk.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] This data is stored as key-value pairs on disk using the storage engine, which is treated primarily as a black-box API.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] CockroachDB uses the Pebble storage engine.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] In addition, there is also a block cache shared amongst all of the stores in a node.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] These stores in turn have a collection of range replicas.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] More than one replica for a range will never be placed on the same store or even the same node.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] CockroachDB uses Pebble––an embedded key-value store inspired by RocksDB, and developed by Cockroach Labs––to read and write data to disk.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] Efficient storage for the keys is guaranteed by the underlying Pebble engine by means of prefix compression.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] For more information about Pebble, see the Pebble GitHub page or the blog post Introducing Pebble: A RocksDB Inspired Key-Value Store Written in Go.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] Pebble uses a Log-structured Merge-tree (*LSM*) to manage data storage.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] For more information about how LSM-based storage engines like Pebble work, see log-structured merge-trees below.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] Pebble uses a Log-structured Merge-tree (hereafter *LSM tree* or *LSM*) to manage data storage.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] At each level of the tree, there are files on disk that store the data referenced at that level.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] The files are known as *sorted string table* files (hereafter *SST* or *SST file*).
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] SSTs are an on-disk representation of sorted lists of key-value pairs.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] SST files are immutable; they are never modified, even during the compaction process.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] Pebble compresses SSTable and blob value data to reduce physical storage use.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] The default profile, `fastest`, uses MinLZ1 on `amd64` and `arm64` platforms, is optimized for low CPU overhead, and is appropriate for most workloads.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] For advanced storage tuning, CockroachDB exposes the `storage.sstable.compression_algorithm` cluster setting.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] The profile values are ordered by increasing compression effort: `fastest`, `fast`, `balanced`, and `good`.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] These profiles enable selective use of Zstd1 depending on the block type, LSM level, and compression benefit.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] Higher-effort profiles use Zstd1 more frequently and can improve compression for some workloads, but can also increase CPU usage for writes, compactions, and reads that decompress data.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] Most users do not need to tune this setting.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] Work with Cockroach Labs Support before changing this setting in production.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] Changing `storage.sstable.compression_algorithm` does not immediately recompress existing SST files.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] SSTs are immutable, so a new setting applies as Pebble writes new SSTs or rewrites existing SSTs during compaction, ingestion, restore, or other SST-writing work.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] During a transition, a store can contain SSTs compressed with multiple algorithms.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] To evaluate the CPU usage vs. size tradeoff for your particular data, use `cockroach debug pebble db analyze-data`.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] Review the results with Cockroach Labs Support before changing the cluster setting.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] You can monitor overall storage compression with the `storage.compression.cr` metric.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] The levels of the LSM are organized from L0 to L6.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] New data is added into L0 (e.g., using `INSERT` or `IMPORT INTO`) and then merged down into lower levels over time.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] The diagram below shows what an LSM looks like at a high level.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] Each level is associated with a set of SSTs.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] Each SST is immutable and has a unique, monotonically increasing number.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] The SSTs within each level are guaranteed to be non-overlapping: for example, if one SST contains the keys `[A-F)` (noninclusive), the next will contain keys `[F-R)`, and so on.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] The L0 level is a special case: it is the only level of the tree that is allowed to contain SSTs with overlapping keys.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] This tradeoff between compactions and write amplification is necessary, because if the storage engine performs too few compactions, the size of L0 will get too large and an inverted LSM will result, which also has ill effects.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] In contrast, writes to the WAL are a small fraction of a store's overall write bandwidth and IOPS.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] Read amplification is high when the LSM is inverted.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] In the inverted LSM state, reads need to start in higher levels and "look down" through a lot of SSTs to read a key's correct (freshest) value.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] Read amplification can be especially bad if a large `IMPORT INTO` is overloading the cluster (due to insufficient CPU and/or IOPS) and the storage engine has to consult many small SSTs in L0 to determine the most up-to-date value of the keys being read (e.g., using a `SELECT`).
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] A certain amount of read amplification is expected in a normally functioning CockroachDB cluster.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] For example, a read amplification factor less than 10 as shown in the **Read Amplification** graph on the **Storage** dashboard is considered healthy.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] The storage engine can optimize performance using *value separation*.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] When the engine encounters a key-value pair with a sufficiently large value component, it stores the key in the LSM alongside a pointer to the value's location in a *blob file* that is located outside the LSM.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] This indirection allows compactions of the LSM to skip rewriting large values over and over; instead, compactions can copy a pointer to the large value's location.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] Value separation is especially beneficial for workloads with large values relative to key size (for example, Raft log entries).
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] It reduces write amplification by about 50%, at the cost of about 20% in space amplification.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] In practice, value separation causes the storage engine to use far fewer IOPS and storage bandwidth overall, which are expensive, at the cost of an increase in storage capacity, which is much cheaper.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] The process of merging SSTs and moving them from L0 down to L6 in the LSM is called *compaction*.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] The storage engine works to compact data as quickly as possible.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] As a result of this process, lower levels of the LSM should contain larger SSTs that contain less recently updated keys, while higher levels of the LSM should contain smaller SSTs that contain more recently updated keys.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] The compaction process is necessary in order for an LSM to work efficiently; from L0 down to L6, each level of the tree should have about 1/10 as much data as the next level below.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] E.g., L1 should have about 1/10 as much data as L2, and so on.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] Ideally as much of the data as possible will be stored in larger SSTs referenced at lower levels of the LSM.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] If the compaction process falls behind, it can result in an inverted LSM.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] SST files are never modified during the compaction process.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] Instead, new SSTs are written, and old SSTs are deleted.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] This design takes advantage of the fact that sequential disk access is much, much faster than random disk access.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] The process of compaction works like this: if two SST files *A* and *B* need to be merged, their contents (key-value pairs) are read into memory.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] From there, the contents are sorted and merged together in memory, and a new file *C* is opened and written to disk with the new, larger sorted list of key-value pairs.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] This step is conceptually similar to a merge sort.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] Finally, the old files *A* and *B* are deleted.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] By default, the storage engine uses a compaction concurrency of 3.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] If you have sufficient IOPS and CPU headroom, you can consider increasing this setting via the `COCKROACH_COMPACTION_CONCURRENCY` environment variable.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] This may help to reshape the LSM more quickly in inverted LSM scenarios; and it can lead to increased overall performance for some workloads.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] Cockroach Labs **strongly recommends** testing your workload against non-default values of this setting.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] If the compaction process falls behind the amount of data being added, and there is more data stored at a higher level of the tree than the level below, the LSM shape can become inverted.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] During normal operation, the LSM should look like this: ◣.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] An inverted LSM will have degraded read performance.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] Inverted LSMs also have excessive compaction debt.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] In this state, the storage engine has a large backlog of compactions to do to return the inverted LSM to a normal, non-inverted state.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] For instructions showing how to monitor your cluster's LSM health, see LSM Health.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] To monitor your cluster's LSM L0 health, see IO Overload.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] To facilitate managing the LSM tree structure, the storage engine maintains an in-memory representation of the LSM known as the *memtable*; periodically, data from the memtable is flushed to SST files on disk.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] Another file on disk called the write-ahead log (hereafter *WAL*) is associated with each memtable to ensure durability in case of power loss or other failures.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] The WAL is where the freshest updates issued to the storage engine by the replication layer are stored on disk.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] Each WAL has a 1 to 1 correspondence with a memtable; they are kept in sync, and updates from the WAL and memtable are written to SSTs periodically as part of the storage engine's normal operation.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] The relationship between the memtable, the WAL, and the SST files is shown in the diagram below.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] New values are written to the WAL at the same time as they are written to the memtable.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] From the memtable they are eventually written to SST files on disk for longer-term storage.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] The LSM tree design optimizes write performance over read performance.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] By keeping sorted key-value data in SSTs, it avoids random disk seeks when writing.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] It tries to mitigate the cost of reads (random seeks) by doing reads from as low in the LSM tree as possible, from fewer, larger files.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] This is why the storage engine performs compactions.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] The storage engine also uses a block cache to speed up reads even further whenever possible.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] The tradeoffs in the LSM design are meant to take advantage of the way modern disks work, since even though they provide faster reads of random locations on disk due to caches, they still perform relatively poorly on writes to random locations.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] CockroachDB relies heavily on multi-version concurrency control (MVCC) to process concurrent requests and guarantee consistency.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] Much of this work is done by using hybrid logical clock (HLC) timestamps to differentiate between versions of data, track commit timestamps, and identify a value's garbage collection expiration.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] All of this MVCC data is then stored in Pebble.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] Despite being implemented in the storage layer, MVCC values are widely used to enforce consistency in the transaction layer.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] For example, CockroachDB maintains a timestamp cache, which stores the timestamp of the last time that the key was read.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] If a write operation occurs at a lower timestamp than the largest value in the read timestamp cache, it signifies that there is a potential anomaly.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] Under the default `SERIALIZABLE` isolation level, the transaction must be restarted at a later timestamp.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] As described in the SQL:2011 standard, CockroachDB supports time travel queries (enabled by MVCC).
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] To do this, all of the schema information also has an MVCC-like model behind it.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] This lets you perform `SELECT...AS OF SYSTEM TIME`, and CockroachDB uses the schema information as of that time to formulate the queries.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] Using these tools, you can get consistent data from your database as far back as your garbage collection period.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] CockroachDB regularly garbage collects MVCC values to reduce the size of data stored on disk.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] To do this, we compact old MVCC values when there is a newer MVCC value with a timestamp that's older than the garbage collection period.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] The garbage collection period can be set at the cluster, database, or table level by configuring the `gc.ttlseconds` replication zone variable.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] For more information about replication zones, see Replication Controls.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] Garbage collection can only run on MVCC values which are not covered by a *protected timestamp*.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] Protected timestamps ensure the safety of historical data while also enabling shorter GC TTLs.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] A shorter GC TTL means that fewer previous MVCC values are kept around.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] This can help lower query execution costs for workloads which update rows frequently throughout the day, since the SQL layer has to scan over previous MVCC values to find the current value of a row.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] Protected timestamps work by creating *protection records*, which are stored in an internal system table.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] When a long-running job such as a backup wants to protect data at a certain timestamp from being garbage collected, it creates a protection record associated with that data and timestamp.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] Upon successful creation of a protection record, the MVCC values for the specified data at timestamps less than or equal to the protected timestamp will not be garbage collected.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] When the job that created the protection record finishes its work, it removes the record, allowing the garbage collector to run on the formerly protected values.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] For further detail on protected timestamps, see the Cockroach Labs Blog Protected Timestamps: For a future with less garbage.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] The storage layer commits writes from the Raft log to disk, as well as returns requested data (i.e., reads) to the replication layer.
[src:cockroachdb/storage-layer] Now that you've learned about our architecture, start up a CockroachDB Standard cluster or local cluster and start developing with CockroachDB.
